# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The **1930 British Empire Games** were the inaugural edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, and was held in Hamilton, Ontario, from 16 to 23 August 1930.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was organized by *Hamilton Spectator* sportswriter Bobby Robinson after he attended the 1928 Summer Olympics in Amsterdam as manager of the Canadian track and field team and was inspired to create a similar event for the British Empire.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] After campaigning for the idea among contacts he met at the Olympics, he was asked to organise the first British Empire Games in Hamilton.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] Fellow Hamilton journalist Ivan Miller helped with the organizing committee.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The sports included athletics, boxing, lawn bowls, rowing, swimming, and wrestling.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony and athletics events were held at Civic Stadium (later renamed Ivor Wynne Stadium) in east Hamilton.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was opened by the Governor General of Canada, Lord Willingdon, on 16 August.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] Canadian triple jumper Gordon Smallacombe claimed the debut gold medal a few hours later.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The 1930 British Empire Games made use of pedestals for dignitaries to present medals to winning athletes, as proposed by Bobby Robinson.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] This inspired the Olympic medal podium ceremonies which began at the 1932 Winter Olympics.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The **1934 British Empire Games** were the second edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, held in England, from 4–11 August 1934.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The host city was London, with the main venues at Wembley Park and the White City Stadium, although the track cycling events were in Manchester.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Seventeen national teams took part, including the Irish Free State (the only Games in which they participated, although an all-Ireland team competed at the 1930 Games).
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The 1934 Games had been originally awarded to Johannesburg, South Africa, but the change of venue to London was made due to concerns regarding the treatment of black and Asian athletes by South African officials and fans.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Six sports were featured in the Games with rowing being dropped from 1930 but cycling making its first appearance.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Athletics took place at the White City Stadium, while boxing, wrestling, and aquatics (swimming and diving) were held at the Wembley Empire Pool, where the swimming pool would be converted overnight into an arena with 7,000 additional seats brought in to increase the capacity to 12,000.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Lawn bowls was held at two clubs in Paddington and Temple, while the cycling was held at the Fallowfield Stadium in Manchester.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Events for women athletes included a debut in athletics; the previous games had women's events in swimming and diving only.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The Wembley Empire Pool was built specifically for the games on the instruction of Arthur Elvin and had been completed in just nine months, opening 10 days before the start of the Games on 25 July.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] (Teams participating for the first time in **bold**).
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] The **1938 British Empire Games** were the third British Empire Games, the event that evolved to become the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Held in Sydney, Australia, from 5–12 February 1938, they were timed to coincide with Sydney's sesqui-centenary (150 years since the foundation of British settlement in Australia).
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Venues included the Sydney Cricket Ground (the main stadium), the North Sydney Olympic Pool and Henson Park.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] An estimated 40,000 people attended the opening ceremony.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] A men's residential village was established within the grounds of the Sydney Showground, while the female athletes were housed in hotels.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] The star of the games was the Australian athlete Decima Norman, who won five gold medals in track and field.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Margaret Dovey, later married to Australian prime minister Gough Whitlam, finished sixth in the 220 yards breaststroke.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Due to the onset of World War II, the games were not held again until 1950.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The **1950 British Empire Games** were the fourth staging of what is now called the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] It was held in Auckland, New Zealand, between 4 and 11 February 1950, after a 12-year gap from the third edition of the games due to World War II.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The fourth games were originally awarded to Montreal, Canada and were to be held in 1942 but were cancelled due to the War.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The Games were declared open by Sir Bernard Freyberg.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony was held at Eden Park and was sold out with 40,000 people attending.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] Eden Park also served as the main venue, while the closing ceremonies were held at Western Springs Stadium.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] Other venues included the Auckland Town Hall and the Newmarket Olympic Pool.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] A 1950 British Empire Games documentary film of the games was made by the New Zealand National Film Unit.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] At the 1950 British Empire Games all the teams won at least one medal.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** were held in Vancouver, British Columbia, from 30 July to 7 August 1954.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the fifth edition of the event that would eventually become known as the Commonwealth Games, the second post-war Games, the second Canadian Games after the inaugural event in Hamilton and the first event since the name change from British Empire Games took effect in 1952.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Other bids to stage the Games were received from Toronto, Montreal and Hamilton.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The main venue was the Empire Stadium, which had been specifically constructed for the games at the cost of £500,000.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Work on the 25,000 seated stadium started in October 1953 and the keys were handed over to Stan Smith (General chairman of the games) on 12 July 1954.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The games were attended by 24 nations and 662 competitors.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the first time that the games gained a television audience, when CBC and NBC transmitted pictures to an estimated 100 million North American viewers.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Recordings of the games were also shown on the BBC Television Service, beginning a consistent association between the BBC and the Commonwealth Games which only ended in 2026.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was at these games that the "Miracle Mile" took place between Roger Bannister and John Landy at the Empire Stadium.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the first time these two (and at that time the only two) sub-four-minute mile runners appeared in the same race, and also the first time two runners broke four minutes in the same race.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] On the same afternoon, Jim Peters, the holder of the world best time for the marathon, entered the stadium 17 minutes ahead of his nearest rival, but collapsed on his final lap, and never completed the race.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 24 teams were represented at the 1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** (Welsh: *Gemau Ymerodraeth Prydain a'r Gymanwlad* 1958) were held in Cardiff, Wales, from 18 to 26 July 1958.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the sixth edition of what would come to be known as the Commonwealth Games, the second Games held in the United Kingdom, and the second held under the name **British Empire and Commonwealth Games**.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Thirty-five nations sent a total of 1,130 athletes and 228 officials to the Cardiff Games and 23 countries and dependencies won medals, including, for the first time, Singapore, Ghana, Kenya and the Isle of Man.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 178,000 tickets were eventually sold during the Games.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The Cardiff Games introduced the Queen's Baton Relay, which has been conducted as a prelude to every Commonwealth Games ever since.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The British Empire and Commonwealth Games, including the opening and closing ceremonies, were held at the Cardiff Arms Park.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The following venues were used during the Games.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 36 countries and territories were represented (and 1,100 athletes), being the largest number to date, with a significant number of teams competing for the first time at the 1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] At Cardiff Arms Park, an anti-apartheid crowd protested at the all-white South African team; games organisers responded that non-white South Africans were ineligible as their associations were not affiliated to the international federations.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] South Africa left the Commonwealth in 1961 and next appeared at the Games in 1994.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] Rome had previously been awarded the administration of the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] However, following the eruption of Mount Vesuvius in 1906, the city had no choice but to decline and pass the honour to London.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union won the most gold and overall medals at the 1960 Games.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] The 1st Paralympic Games were held in Rome in conjunction with the 1960 Summer Olympics, marking the first time such events coincided.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] On 15 June 1955, at the 50th IOC Session in Paris, France, Rome won the right to host the 1960 Games, having beaten Brussels, Mexico City, Tokyo, Detroit, Budapest and finally Lausanne.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] Tokyo and Mexico City would subsequently host the proceeding 1964 and 1968 Summer Olympics respectively.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] Toronto was initially interested in the bidding, but was automatically removed from consideration when it failed to return the IOC's mandatory questionnaire by the deadline.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] The questionnaire may have been mislaid in the confusion following the death of the Toronto bid's chief organiser, Robert Hood Saunders, in a plane crash weeks before the deadline.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] This was the first of five unsuccessful attempts by Toronto to secure the Summer Olympics, the most recent being a bid for the 2008 Games.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] 1 New facilities constructed in preparation for the Olympic Games.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] 2 Existing facilities modified or refurbished in preparation for the Olympic Games.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] A total of 83 nations participated at the Rome Games.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] Athletes from Morocco, San Marino, Sudan, and Tunisia competed at the Olympic Games for the first time.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] Athletes from Barbados, Jamaica and Trinidad and Tobago would represent the new (British) West Indies Federation, competing as "Antilles", but this nation would only exist for this single Olympiad.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] Athletes from Northern Rhodesia and Southern Rhodesia competed under the Rhodesia name while representing the Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] Athletes from East Germany and West Germany would compete as the United Team of Germany from 1956 to 1964.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] Athletes from the People's Republic of China last competed at the 1952 Summer Games but had since withdrawn from the Olympic movement due to a dispute with the Republic of China over the right to represent China.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] The number in parentheses indicates the number of participants that each country contributed.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] The 1960 Summer Olympics featured 17 different sports encompassing 23 disciplines, and medals were awarded in 150 events.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1960-summer-olympics] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1966 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** were held in Kingston, Jamaica, from 4 to 13 August 1966.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the first time that the Games had been held outside the so-called White Dominions.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The opening ceremony was the first Games to be opened in the evening.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The event was followed by the 1966 Commonwealth Paraplegic Games for wheelchair athletes.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Jamaica remains the only host nation of a Commonwealth Games that did not win at least one gold medal in its own games.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Two sports; lawn bowls and rowing were dropped from the Games due to lack of facilities and were replaced by the debut sports of badminton and shooting.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] A record 38 countries competed at the Games.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Kingston was elected host by the CGF in Rome, Italy, during the 1960 Summer Olympics.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 34 teams were represented at the 1966 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1966-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] (Teams competing for the first time are shown in **bold**).
